<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Resources</strong> aims to decouple the <em>specification</em> of a data request from its <em>execution</em>.
        It provides a standard interoperability layer for Middleware (Auth, Logging) and Caching that works across any transport (REST, GraphQL, WebSocket).
    </p>
</section>
<section id="proposed-resources" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="proposed-standards">Proposed Standards</h3>
    <div class="standards-grid">
        {% for resource in resources %}
        <a href="/resources/{{ resource.id }}/" class="standard-card">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <h4 id="resource-{{ resource.id }}" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">{{ resource.name }}</h4>
            </div>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">{{ resource.summary }}</p>
            <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                {{ projectStatus(resource.status) }}
            </div>
        </a>
        {% endfor %}
    </div>
</section>

<section id="ssr" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Resources</strong>.
        The server MUST execute data requests at render time and embed the results directly in the HTML.
        Clients receive pre-fetched data and skip redundant network requests during hydration.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Fetched data embedding</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;script type="application/json"
  data-store="resource:users"&gt;
[{"id":1,"name":"Alice"},
 {"id":2,"name":"Bob"}]
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST execute the resource request and serialize the response using the <a href="/projects/webstates/#ssr">Web States</a> JSON block format. The <code>data-store</code> key uses a <code>resource:</code> prefix to distinguish resource data from application state.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Resource state templates</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;!-- Server renders the success
     template with fetched data --&gt;
&lt;ul class="user-list"&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Alice&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Bob&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST render the appropriate state template (success, error, or empty) based on the fetch result. See <a href="/projects/webdirectives/#ssr">Web Directives SSR</a> for <code>resource:loader</code> directive expansion.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Prefetch hints</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;link rel="prefetch"
  href="/api/users?page=2"&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MAY emit <code>&lt;link rel="prefetch"&gt;</code> hints for resources the client is likely to need next (e.g., next page of paginated data).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Error state</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;div class="error-state"&gt;
  Failed to load users.
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>If the server request fails, the server MUST render the error template rather than leaving the resource in a loading state.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Loading state</strong></td>
                    <td>MUST NOT appear in server output</td>
                    <td>Server output is final — loading/pending states are client-only concepts. The server either succeeds, errors, or returns empty.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Data recovery:</strong> Client reads <code>&lt;script type="application/json" data-store="resource:..."&gt;</code> blocks and initializes resource stores with the pre-fetched data, following the <a href="/projects/webstates/#ssr">Web States</a> hydration contract.</li>
        <li><strong>Skip initial fetch:</strong> If a resource store is hydrated with data, the client MUST skip the initial network request. Subsequent refreshes or invalidations trigger normal fetching.</li>
        <li><strong>Template matching:</strong> The server-rendered template (success/error/empty) should match what the client would render for the same data. No DOM mutations are needed on initial hydration.</li>
        <li><strong>Middleware activation:</strong> Client-side middleware (auth headers, retry logic, caching policies) activates for all subsequent requests after hydration.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript: all resource data is visible as server-rendered content.
        Lists, tables, and detail views display the fetched data as static HTML.
        The JSON script blocks are invisible (<code>type="application/json"</code> is not executed).
        Prefetch hints are honored by the browser's native prefetch mechanism.
        No data refreshing, pagination, or dynamic filtering — content is frozen at its server-rendered state.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Data fetching:</strong> All runtime <code>fetch()</code> calls, polling, WebSocket connections</li>
        <li><strong>Middleware pipeline:</strong> Auth injection, retry logic, request/response transforms</li>
        <li><strong>Cache management:</strong> Stale-while-revalidate, TTL expiry, cache invalidation</li>
        <li><strong>Loading states:</strong> Spinner display, skeleton screens, progress indicators</li>
        <li><strong>Pagination &amp; filtering:</strong> Dynamic data refetching based on user interaction</li>
        <li><strong>Error recovery:</strong> Retry buttons, fallback UI, error boundary integration</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for executing resource requests, serializing responses, and rendering
            the appropriate state template.
            Web Resources does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
            See also: <a href="/projects/webstates/#ssr">Web States SSR Contract</a> for data serialization format,
            <a href="/projects/webdirectives/#ssr">Web Directives SSR Contract</a> for <code>resource:loader</code> expansion.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

